3.3 Aesthetic mapping

ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping=aes(x=displ, y=hwy, color = class))

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, size = class))

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, alpha = class))

# Right
ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, shape = class))

3.3.1 Exercises

  1. What’s gone wrong with this code? Why are the points not blue?
ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = "blue"))

The color of points isn’t blue. The color = “blue” is inside aes() so tried to map aesthics to a variable called “blue” which doesn’t exist.

Possbile. For categorical, multiple aesthetics can be mapped and given one legend. FOr continous, excluding shape, get two legends.

  1. What does stroke aesthetic do?
?geom_point

To modify width of border for shapes that have a border.

ggplot(mtcars, aes(wt, mpg)) +
  geom_point(shape = 12, colour = "black", fill = "white", size = 5, stroke = 3)

ggplot(mtcars, aes(wt, mpg)) +
  geom_point(shape = 10, colour = "black", fill = "white", size = 5)

Becomes a boolean

3.5 Facets

To split into subplots, categorical variables facet_wrap(~ )

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  facet_wrap(~ class, nrow = 2)

Can facet by two variables facet_grid( ~ )

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  facet_grid(drv ~ cyl)

3.5.1 Exercises

  1. What happens if facet on a continuous variable?
ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  facet_wrap(~ hwy)

Makes each number in continuous variable into discrete category

  1. What do the empty cells in plot with facet_grid(drv ~ cyl) mean? How do they relate to this plot?
ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = drv, y = cyl))

ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x=drv, y=cyl)) + facet_grid(drv~cyl)

Empty cells mean there is not data point for that coordinate of drv, cyl. The empty cells relate to the absence of data point in that coordinate.

  1. What plots does the following code make? What does . do?
ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
  facet_grid(drv ~ .)

## scatterplot of displ versus hwy, faceted based on wheel drive

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
  facet_grid(. ~ cyl)

## scatterplot of disp versus hwy, faceted based on # of cyl

The . prevents faceting in row or columns dimension when faceting. From ?facet_grid: “the dot in the formula is used to indicate there should be no faceting on this dimension (either row or column).”

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
  facet_wrap(~ cyl)

but how is it different from below: if you ommit the .

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
  facet_grid(~ cyl)

  1. What are the advantages to using faceting instead of the colour aesthetic? What are the disadvantages? How might the balance change if you had a larger dataset?
ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  facet_wrap(~ class, nrow = 2)

Adv: Less crowded, can look at data separated by subsetting Dis: Taken away from whole, hard to see how different subsets of data might be driving whole data trends More faceting as dataset gets larger

  1. Read ?facet_wrap
?facet_wrap

nrow indicate number of rows for facets ncol indicate number of cols for facets

facet_grid doesn’t have nrow or ncol variables because that’s pre-defined in the facetting variables for facets

  1. When using facet_grid() you should usually put the variable with more unique levels in the columns. Why?

Better use of screen space. Computer screens wider than they are tall.
